    <!-- Introduction -->
    <section id="intro">
      <h2>Introduction: When God Speaks, But Life Looks Different</h2>
<p><strong>Genesis 12:4-5</strong>  So Abram went, as the Lord had told him; and Lot went with him. Abram was seventy-five years old when he set out from Harran. 5 He took his wife Sarai, his nephew Lot, all the possessions they had accumulated and the people they had acquired in Harran, and they set out for the land of Canaan, and they arrived there.
<p><strong>Genesis 15:4-6 </strong> Then the word of the Lord came to him: “This man will not be your heir, but a son who is your own flesh and blood will be your heir.” 5 He took him outside and said, “Look up at the sky and count the stars—if indeed you can count them.” Then he said to him, “So shall your offspring be.” 6 Abram believed the Lord, and he credited it to him as righteousness
Looking at Abraham’s situation, having Ismael was a fulfilment of that promise but God said no, in the process, God expect us to follow, not to go our own way. 
<p><strong>Proverbs 14:12</strong> There is a way that appears to be right, but in the end, it leads to death.</p>
Our ways may momentarily looks the perfect solution, but we may regret ever settling on such as an answer.</p>
Birth of Isaac: Isaac was born when Abraham was 100 years old and Sarah was 90
 <p><strong>Genesis 21:5</strong> Abraham was a hundred years old when his son Isaac was born to him.</p>
So, if we were to do a little Calculation, 100 − 75 = <strong>25</strong> years of waiting between the promise and its fulfillment.</p>
This long waiting period highlights God’s perfect timing and the importance of faith and patience during the Process.
<p> "Many believers struggle not with hearing God's promises, but with enduring the Process that brings them to pass."</p>
<p>Welcome to the prophecy and the Process</p>
    </section>

<!-- Chapter 1 -->
<section id="chapter1">
    <h2>Chapter 1: The Blueprint of Heaven</h2>
    <blockquote>“For I know the plans I have for you,” declares the LORD, “plans to prosper you and not to harm you, plans to give you hope and a future.” — Jeremiah 29:11</blockquote>
    <p>Every building begins with a plan… Your life is not a random accident…</p>

    <div class="scripture">
        <h3>Scripture Meditation:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Psalm 139:16</li>
            <li>Jeremiah 29:11</li>
            <li>Hebrews 11:8</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="reflection">
        <h3>Reflection Questions:</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>What parts of my life feel like they lack a blueprint right now?</li>
            <li>Can I identify a moment where God revealed just enough light for me to take the next step?</li>
            <li>What fears do I need to surrender so I can trust His design?</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="prayer">
        <h3>Prayer Declaration:</h3>
        <p>“Father, I thank You that my life is not random. You wrote my story before I lived it. Even when I do not see the full picture, I trust that You hold the blueprint of my destiny. Strengthen my faith to walk step by step, believing that Your plans for me are good.”</p>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- Chapter 2 -->
<section id="chapter2">
    <h2>Chapter 2: What is the Prophetic?</h2>
    <blockquote>“Surely the Sovereign LORD does nothing without revealing his plan to his servants the prophets.” — Amos 3:7</blockquote>
    <p>The word “prophetic” often stirs mixed reactions… The Prophetic is heaven’s perspective invading earth’s confusion…</p>

    <div class="scripture">
        <h3>Scripture Meditation:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Amos 3:7</li>
            <li>Psalm 119:105</li>
            <li>1 Timothy 1:18</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="reflection">
        <h3>Reflection Questions:</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>What prophetic words or scriptures have I received that I need to hold onto again?</li>
            <li>Am I treating prophecy like a compass (direction) or like a map (details)?</li>
            <li>How can I rehearse God’s promises in my heart when circumstances seem opposite?</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="prayer">
        <h3>Prayer Declaration:</h3>
        <p>“Lord, I thank You for speaking over my life. Your word is my anchor and compass. Help me to discern Your voice, to believe Your promises, and to walk boldly in the direction You set before me. Even when I cannot see the full map, I trust the light You give me for the next step.”</p>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- Chapter 3 -->
<section id="chapter3">
    <h2>Chapter 3: What is the Process?</h2>
    <blockquote>“Not only so, but we also glory in our sufferings, because we know that suffering produces perseverance; perseverance, character; and character, hope.” — Romans 5:3–4</blockquote>
    <p>If the Prophetic is the spark that ignites hope, then the Process is the furnace that refines faith…</p>

    <div class="scripture">
        <h3>Scripture Meditation:</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Romans 5:3–5</li>
            <li>Habakkuk 2:3</li>
            <li>James 1:2–4</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="reflection">
        <h3>Reflection Questions:</h3>
        <ol>
            <li>What season of Process am I currently walking through?</li>
            <li>How might God be using this season to shape my character or increase my capacity?</li>
            <li>What do I need to release so I can embrace the Process with faith instead of frustration?</li>
        </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="prayer">
        <h3>Prayer Declaration:</h3>
        <p>“Lord, I surrender to the Process. Though I do not always understand the delays, I trust that You are working all things for my good. Build in me the character, endurance, and faith to carry what You have promised. I believe that what You have spoken will surely come to pass in Your perfect timing.”</p>
    </div>
</section>

